This is a known change. In .NET 10, MAUI defaults to **edge-to-edge** rendering on Android, and `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated at the Android API 30 level. MAUI's replacement is **`KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`**, which is enabled by default.

Here's what to do for a chat screen:

### 1. Ensure your layout is keyboard-friendly

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:android="clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.AndroidSpecific;
             assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls">
  <Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}"
                    ItemTemplate="{StaticResource MessageTemplate}" />
    <Grid Grid.Row="1" Padding="8" ColumnDefinitions="*, Auto">
      <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." />
      <Button Grid.Column="1" Text="Send" />
    </Grid>
  </Grid>
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. Set `adjustResize` in `AndroidManifest.xml`

```xml
<activity
    ...
    android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" />
```

This still tells Android your app wants to resize for the keyboard—edge-to-edge then uses **window insets** to actually do it.

### 3. If the auto-scroll isn't enough, handle insets manually

In your `MainActivity.cs` or a custom handler:

```csharp
#if ANDROID
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using AndroidX.Core.Graphics;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Edge-to-edge is already on in .NET 10; just consume the IME inset
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
            Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!,
            new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }

    private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use whichever is larger — keyboard or nav bar
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
#endif
```

### Quick summary

| .NET 9 approach | .NET 10 replacement |
|---|---|
| `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` | `adjustResize` in manifest + edge-to-edge insets |
| Manual resize hacks | `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (on by default) |
| — | `SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener` for fine control |

**Try steps 1–2 first**—`KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` + `adjustResize` handles most cases. Only add step 3 if the input bar still gets covered. On **iOS**, no extra work is needed; MAUI's auto-scroll handles it automatically.
